    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-06-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-06-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="366"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d366">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.52/6–1650</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the <gloss type="from">President</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-06-16">June 16,
                            1950</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have been studying the National Security Council report by the Secretary of
                    Defense on the United States policy toward Germany and Spain.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d366fn1">For the text of the report on Germany, see <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 71, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>. For the
                        text of the report on Spain, see Bradley’s memorandum to Johnson, May 3,
                            <ref target="frus1950v03#pg_1560">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p.
                            1560</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>These two reports are decidedly militaristic and in my opinion not realistic with
                    present conditions. I wish you would look them over carefully and discuss them
                    with me Monday when you come in for the conference.<note n="2" xml:id="d366fn2"
                        >At their meeting on June 19, Secretary Acheson reviewed the position of the
                        Department of State on Spain and Germany and offered to put their substance
                        into memoranda for the President. For the views on Germany, see <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 71/1, July 3, <ref target="#pg_691">p.
                            691</ref>; for the views on Spain, see <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> 72/1, July 3, <ref target="frus1950v03#pg_1570">vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 1570</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>H[<hi rend="smallcaps">arry</hi>] S. T[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >ruman</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
